quizzes.textContent:
[h1]else if[/h1]

You can use the [b]else if statement[/b] to specify a new condition if the first condition is false.

[b]Example:[/b] [code format="js" codeId="663"]var course = 1;
[b]if [/b](course == 1) {
   document.write("<h1>HTML Tutorial</h1>");
} [b]else if [/b](course == 2) {
   document.write("<h1>CSS Tutorial</h1>");
} [b]else [/b]{
   document.write("<h1>JavaScript Tutorial</h1>");
}[/code]
The above code says:
- [b]if[/b] course is equal to 1, output "HTML Tutorial";
- [b]else, if[/b] course is equal to 2, output "CSS Tutorial";
- if none of the above condition is true, then output "JavaScript Tutorial";

[b]course [/b]is equal to 1, so we get the following result: [img id="2753" width="100%"]
[note]The final [b]else [/b]statement "ends" the else if statement and should be always written after the [b]if [/b]and [b]else if[/b] statements.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to create a valid if...else...if statement:
[!raw!]
var status = 1;
var msg;
{0} (status == 1) {
   msg = "Online";
}
 {1} (status == 2) {
   msg = "Away";
} 
else {
   msg = "Offline";
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]else if[/h1]

The final [b]else[/b] block will be executed when [b]none[/b] of the conditions is true. 

Let's change the value of the [b]course [/b]variable in our previous example. [code format="js" codeId="664"]var course = 3;
if (course == 1) {
   document.write("<h1>HTML Tutorial</h1>");
} else if (course == 2) {
   document.write("<h1>CSS Tutorial</h1>");
} else {
   document.write("<h1>JavaScript Tutorial</h1>");
}[/code]
[b]The result: [/b] [img id="2754" width="100%"]
[note]You can write as many [b]else if[/b] statements as you need.[/note]
